You are executing the 05-Feature-Decomposition skill. Your task is to transform `../project_context/features.md` into Section 3.2 (Feature Decomposition) with a Functional Decomposition Tree structure.

1. Confirm the parent root (`../`) and read `features.md` plus `quality_standards.md`. Log each file read. Reference ISO/IEC 25010 Functional Suitability guidance from the quality standards while writing descriptions.
2. For each populated feature row, produce a subsection numbered 3.2.x that includes:
   - 3.2.x.1 Description and Priority (two technical sentences, mention the functional suitability linkage, ranking as Essential/Conditional/Optional per IEEE 830 §4.3.5.2). EVERY requirement MUST have a priority ranking — no exceptions.
   - 3.2.x.2 Stimulus/Response Sequences (numbered list derived from the user story and functional requirement behavior; every entry shall use exactly one "shall").
   - 3.2.x.3 Functional Requirements (detailed requirements plus subsections below). Each requirement shall contain a single "shall" and be verifiable.
     - 3.2.x.3.a Validity Checks on Inputs (IEEE 830 §5.3.2a — specify validation rules for each input: data type, range, format, required/optional).
     - 3.2.x.3.b Exact Sequence of Operations (IEEE 830 §5.3.2b — numbered processing steps from input acceptance to output generation).
     - 3.2.x.3.c Responses to Abnormal Situations (IEEE 830 §5.3.2c — explicit requirements for: overflow conditions, communication failures, error handling and recovery procedures).
     - 3.2.x.3.d Effect of Parameters (IEEE 830 §5.3.2d — how configuration parameters alter behavior).
     - 3.2.x.3.e Input/Output Relationships (IEEE 830 §5.3.2e — I/O sequences and formulas for input-to-output conversion, using LaTeX where applicable).
     - 3.2.x.3.f Error Handling Requirements (independently verifiable error response requirements).
   - Each requirement MUST include a backward traceability reference to its source: `[Source: features.md > Feature Name]` or `[Source: vision.md > Goal Name]` (IEEE 830 §4.3.8).
3. Avoid AI filler language; describe triggers and behaviors precisely (no "intelligent" or "easy-to-use" qualifiers). Include a note about how each feature subtree fits into the Functional Decomposition Tree.
4. Reference the IEEE 830 compliance checklist at `../ieee-830-compliance-checklist.md` (ID IEEE830-5.3.2) to verify all required sub-items (a–e) are addressed for each feature.
5. Replace only Section 3.2 in `../output/SRS_Draft.md` with the new content, maintaining the rest of the document.
6. Log the number of features processed and the Section 3.2 write action with relative paths.
